			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64783759" name="comment_link_64783759" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23452577&amp;cid=64783759" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64783759)" >Carving it in Stone</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64783759" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64783759); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Roger+W+Moore">Roger W Moore</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Roger+W+Moore">( 538166 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64783759"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64783759">It depends. If longevity is your only concern then carving it in stone, preferably something hard like granite, is probably still state of the art but the storage time and data capacity is not great. Parchment and vellum with the right inks and storage conditions last pretty well too. Most modern media have far better capacities and write times but rely on small clusters of atoms that make them susceptible to thermodynamic fluctuations and/or cosmic rays/radioactivity over decade plus timescales.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64783759">

</div>
