	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64783621"><p>A company like Iron Mountain should know hard drives, even in optimal conditions, don't last for more than a few years if not in use. Some of the drives will be recoverable, but only at great expense.</p><p>The current best practice for long-term data storage is to transfer to actual archival-quality formats, then re-transfer every decade or so. This avoids rot. (If it were actually archival quality, maybe even longer gaps.)</p><p>Once the (practically mythological) storage on crystal is mastered, then archive to that. B<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
